nforce the conventional sex/gender system and political-economic status quo. In addition, Robertson interrogates the notion of human exceptionalism as she considers whether “civil rights” should be granted to robots. Similarly, she juxtaposes how robots and robotic exoskeletons reinforce a conception of the “normal” body with a deconstruction of the much-invoked Theory of the Uncanny Valley.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mai 2023) 0aHuman-robot interactionzJapan. 70(DE-601)1061832490(DE-588)4050208-9aRoboter2gnd 70(DE-601)1062312860(DE-588)4038639-9aMensch2gnd 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / General.2bisacsh  aandroids.  aanimaloids.  acivil rights.  aethnographic research.  afamily.  agender norms.  agender studies.  ahuman exceptionalism.  ahuman robot coexistence.  ahumanity.  ahumanoid robots.  ajapan.  ajapanese culture.  ajapanese.  amass media.  apostindustrial society.  apress releases.  apublic relations video.  arobot.  arobotic exoskeletons.  arobots in hospitals.  arobots in offices.  arobots in schools.  arobots in the home.  ascience fiction.  ascientists.  asocial media.  asociocultural history.  atheory of the uncanny valley.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z97831106675540 cprintz978052028320640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780520959064?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520959064423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520959064/original  a978-3-11-066755-4  University of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY